    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-10-03T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-10-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="112"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d112">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/1967: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Mukden</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Myers</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mukden</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-10-03T13:00:00+08:00"
                            >October 3, 1931—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 3—2:54 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Referring to Department’s telegram of October 2nd [, 10 a.m.]<note n="90"
                        xml:id="d112fn90">Not printed.</note> Radio station held by Japanese
                    authorities who report it undamaged. Repeated representations to Japanese
                    Consulate relative to reestablishment of service fail to elicit more than
                    statement that the Japanese authorities are considering the matter. Only
                    facility for communication outward is the Japanese telegraph.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Myers</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
